<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Assessment MathML 2.4//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_assessment_mathml_2_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="_u7_introduction_quiz" recommended_attempts="1" max_attempts="6"><title>Integumentary System Introduction</title><page id="f5a4f0a88ee442c0846eda27caae4def"><multiple_choice id="q1" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="aad39cd6ebfb844d8bf77d92adeb46f76">Which of the following is not a function of the integumentary system?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="b953e6ce81064cc2b1ddb3208c1ebc2c" labels="false"><choice value="A">Electrolyte Balance</choice><choice value="B">Thermoregulation</choice><choice value="C">Movement</choice><choice value="D">Sensory reception</choice></input><part id="q1_p1"><skillref idref="integument_function_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="ac4a7a5ffb63f4cbcb5db79efc28f86d2">Incorrect. The integumentary system helps regulate electrolytes through sweating.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa010017630664951baf038332227e1b1">Incorrect. The integumentary system thermoregulates through sweat.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback><p id="afc06eb00bf304e3e8cb0ae1d154597ed">Correct. The integumentary is not responsible for movement. That is the skeletal/muscular system.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="ac1d6fbc45d314550b2808122013a4347">Incorrect. There are sensory receptors located in the integumentary system.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q2" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ad63f7f6152f04b56a593384a4576afab">Keratin and oil work together to make the skin _______?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="d54d45499ea143b3bac2dce3895643fa" labels="false"><choice value="A">sensitive to the environment.</choice><choice value="B">thermoregulatory.</choice><choice value="C">able to produce vitamin D.</choice><choice value="D">water resistant.</choice></input><part id="q2_p1"><skillref idref="integument_function_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="afc5ea8c0335841a7a4e68439dfa0cfd2">Incorrect. The receptor cells allow for sensory reception.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad982fe3ab02b4941a5945ef8ba959c2e">Incorrect. Sweat assist in the thermoregulation.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae6da581989984ff084b207035e7aa8ce">Incorrect. Is secreted from a steroid in the skin.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback><p id="aace8fa8ae32743218a7dc2e36b57fa8b">Correct. Keratin and oils combine to give skin its water resistant property.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q3" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="af38658affa204ef4b6d98b1b1e96bfd9">A burn can be caused by which of the following:</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="f99430c61aeb4e8b827a2ba49807da73" labels="false"><choice value="A">Heat</choice><choice value="B">Electricity</choice><choice value="C">Chemicals</choice><choice value="D">All of the above</choice></input><part id="q3_p1"><skillref idref="integument_function_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="af3b0c30387a94dc6b46c97479b721fba">Partially correct. This is not the only cause of burns.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa48dc6d21f9542d6824abbe2f8df8abf">Partially correct. This is not the only cause of burns.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="af8a6f8ae1e534eafb45cc985e43d52cf">Partially correct. This is not the only cause of burns.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback><p id="adab0d767836b45088e0f7aa77c13f730">Correct. All three of these can cause burns.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q4" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="aa9103c9927c545ceb540f2f2d24a5fde">Which disease is the result of plugged sebaceous gland?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="cd5ec80765604ba68675f80c972b40bf" labels="false"><choice value="A">Psoriasis</choice><choice value="B">Acne</choice><choice value="C">Bed sores</choice><choice value="D">Melanoma</choice></input><part id="q4_p1"><skillref idref="integument_function_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="add1173f460c24056a544238de214a9e6">Incorrect. Psoriasis is caused by an over production of skin cells.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="10"><feedback><p id="ace9c2f4410d94d54999956ac75630b04">Correct. Acne is caused when sebum is clogged in the sebaceous gland.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="adfffc968b69b4fe799f10ca45ebfaeb3">Incorrect. Bed sores can be caused by extended pressure on a an area.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad3c0bd78b435483faab44642e472d461">Incorrect. Melanoma can be caused by UV radiation.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice></page></assessment>
